  * &lt;id_arreglo&gt is the name of the array that you want to traverse with this structure.

268
  When passing by reference, the variable used as an argument in the function/subprocess will actually be the same variable indicated in the call to the function (two identifiers for one single variable). Therefore the function/subprocess will be able to modify that variable. For this to make sense, when invoking the function you must always use a variable as the argument, and not a constant or any other expression (since it would make no sense for the function to try to modify the value of a "constant", for example).
  * Check that all arguments which are defined "by reference" in the function are variables in the invocation/call.
  * If you need to pass a constant or a more general expression to the function, you must modify the function so that the argument in question is received by copy.
 
279
  The subprocess/function indicated in parentheses in the error receives, according to its declaration, a number of arguments/parameters different from the one provided in this call. When invoking a subprocess you must include in the call all the required arguments separated by commas.
  * Check that the argument list is correctly written (each argument separated by a comma).
  * Check that the declaration of the subprocess (using the SubProceso or Función keywords in the pseudocode) is correct.
  * Check that the number of them is equal to the number declared when creating the mentioned subprocess.

292
  Two logical values can only be compared to determine whether they are equal, but there is no ordering relationship between the possible logical values (Verdadero and Falso). Therefore it is not possible to apply the operators &lt;, &gt;, &lt;=, and &gt;= to operands of this data type.
  * Check that the entered expression is correct considering the precedence of the operators involved, and analyzing the type of operands and results for each of them.
  * For example, the expression "3 &lt; x &lt; 7" is incorrect, because it is equivalent to "(3 &lt; x) &lt; 7". So first 3 &lt; x is resolved, which may yield Verdadero or Falso, and then that result (of logical type) is compared with 7.

298  
  The mod operator returns the remainder of an "integer" division, and therefore the operands must be integers. That is, the variables or expressions to the left and right of the operator must both be numeric and evaluate to an integer number. 
  * If one of the operands is not, but you want to use only the integer part of that result, you can use the <A href="funciones.html">Trunc</A> function.

308
  The keyword FINPROCESO was found in a place where it was not expected. This may be due to one of the following three reasons:
  * There are open control structures inside the process that still need to be closed before closing the process. Check that the process control structures are properly nested and closed with their respective FINXXX.
  * The process had already been closed by a previous occurrence of FINPROCESO. Check that FINPROCESO appears only once in the algorithm, and that it is located at the end of a process.
  * You are inside a function or subprocess, in which case you must use FINFUNCIÓN or FUNSUBPROCESO.

310
  Functions or subprocesses that return values must be used as part of expressions. Only subprocesses that do not return any value may be invoked directly.

